profile_positions.description:
ARC provides a comprehensive, integrated solution that transfers weather risk away from governments and enables them to build resilience and better plan, prepare for and respond to extreme weather and natural disaster events. 
Responsibilities:
•	Lead ARC team’s advocacy and communications effort across Member States and support design / implementation of a well aligned Institutional Communication and Communication-for-Development paradigms for effective communication, stakeholder engagement and advocacy at country and regional levels;
•	Work with Government Support Teams to develop strategies to enhance the impact, reach and efficiency of ARC country programmes through multi-stakeholder engagement, storytelling, and evidence-based advocacy;
•	Produce briefs, newsletters, manage the timely delivery of content, and manage relationship with service providers in compliance with ARC branding guidelines;
•	Manage multi-stakeholder relationships and collaborate closely with key stakeholders to achieve ARC’s strategic objectives;
•	Ensure development of frameworks for harmonised messaging, prepare briefs, and provide logistics / tech support to management team / senior staff to engage effectively with the public and media at all forums;
•	Develop specialized campaigns, using storytelling, to ensure country reports and insights are simplified and shared with key decision makers, and internal / external stakeholders;
•	Craft narratives and messages that resonate with ARC strategy aimed at reaching priority audiences including African Union Member States, UN agencies, private sector, development partners, etc.;
•	Improve the quality of communications through the deployment of new skills, gender-transformative reporting for improved impact messaging both within the ARC Group and externally; 
•	Promote advocacy targeted at building smart partnerships with key development institutions to ensure availability, accessibility, and affordability of resources for DRM activities.

In charge of the sub-regional implementation of the Central Bank of Nigeria/NEXIM Bank N550billion ($1.85 billion) Export Stimulation Fund for the promotion of non-oil exports in the Manufacturing, Agro-processing, Solid Minerals and Services (MASS) sectors in line with Federal Government’s Economic Recovery and Growth Plan (ERGP) 2017 – 2020, for the diversification of the economy away from oil and gas. 

As the Head of NEXIM Bank for Southeast (Abia, Anambra, Ebonyi, Enugu, Imo) & Sotuh-south States took responsibility for:  
•	Business plan development, Feasibility studies, financial advisory services; 
•	Identified potential prospects/businesses in line with the Banks mandate in Abia, Anambra, Ebonyi, Enugu and Imo States; 
•	Financial inclusion targeting female-headed MSME businesses, and women in nonoil export sector;
•	Provided input in the articulation of the Business Development Division’s strategy/plan for customer acquisition and retention; 
•	Coordinated collaboration with State-level MSMEs for increased participation in the Bank’s programmes and access to trade finance; 
•	Built synergy and alignment with sister Government agencies for more sustainable socioeconomic growth in the nonoil sector; 
•	Identified and supported key women-led cash-crop cooperatives for export orientation and training; and
•	Articulated and executed the Bank’s marketing strategy within the target market segments (agro-allied, manufacturing, services, and solid minerals) within the region.

•	Developed the department’s strategy (including the branding strategy/policies) in line with the Bank’s strategic objectives; 
•	Developed and managed mutually beneficial relationship between the Bank and key Government institutions, including the Presidency, Legislature, Judiciary and other key stakeholders for efficient pursuit and achievement of the Bank’s vision and mission; 
•	Developed and projected a reputable public image for the Bank to reflect its vision, strategic direction and enhance its competitive positioning; 
•	Managed the corporate transformation and change in the Bank in line with vision to become the leading Export Development agency in Africa by 2015; 
•	Developed and implemented communication framework and guidelines that enhanced the corporate image of the Bank, including policies and guidelines relating to the public conduct of staff and dissemination of information to the media and government; 
•	Managed the Bank’s interface with the government institutions, business groups, media, professional associations, etc.; 
•	Kept abreast of industry and corporate developments, events and issues in support of the Bank’s corporate image and responsibilities; 
•	Developed a framework to gauge the public perception of the Bank and develop appropriate strategies and action steps to ensure alignment of public perception with the image desired by the Bank; 
•	Coordinated the planning, organising and execution of corporate and social events; 
•	Established beneficial relationships with various media houses in support of the Bank’s corporate image and reputation; 
•	Provided guidance and assistance in the conduct of product/ service campaigns/ programs to ensure adequate public appeal and media coverage; 
•	Managed and updated the Bank’s website; 
•	Managed the interface with agencies, institutions, associations e.g. Local and State Governments etc., in the execution of Bank’s role as a responsible corporate citizen.

•	Supported Sector-based employment and social protection activities in the sub-region in accordance with the Recommendations of the Advisory Body on Monetary and Financial Policy for rethinking and monitoring financial stability while generating employment and poverty reduction; 
•	Provided support to constituents to develop processes and guidance for skills policies that maximised the employment impact of economic growth prioritising investments and gender-inclusive development;
•	Strengthened social dialogue and promoted good industrial relations at the national and regional levels;
•	Strengthened labour relations among Government, Employers’ and Trade Union and civil society for better coalition and collaboration in the countries covered by the Office;
•	Facilitate and supported the establishment of multi-sectoral national partnership forum led by United Nations Assistance Development Framework for broad application of the International Labour Standards in the World of Work, especially in the informal economy;
•	Promoted private sector mobilization and participation in the promotion of HIV/AIDS workplace policies and programmes through the development of co-investment projects with ILO constituents 
•	Supported processes to develop and strengthen strategic partnerships for better coalition between the Government, Labour, and other constituencies of the ILO, including the civil society and CBOs in West Africa;
•	Supported the establishment of multi-sectoral national partnership forum led by the Joint UN Teams on AIDS (JUNTA) and other National HIV Coordinating Authorities towards ensuring a broad application of the ILO Code of Practice for HIV/AIDS in the World of Work, especially in the informal economy; and
•	Developed strategies to address the linkages between HIV/AIDS and Child Labour in qualitative and quantitative terms towards addressing the peculiar needs of HIV single mothers / orphans through provision of social security.

•	Assisted in harmonizing procedures and systems for encouraging sustained and meaningful partnerships between the ILO and African political structures such as the AU, NEPAD etc., as well as civil society and the private sector in efforts to halt and begin to reverse the HIV/AIDS in 15 English-speaking African countries;
•	Contributed to strengthening multi-sectoral response to Child Labour and HIV/AIDS in the field of work through providing technical support to constituents in the areas of Prevention, Care and Support as well as Stigma, discrimination and human rights;
•	Facilitated and supported the development and strengthening of regional collaborations and meaningful partnerships among the ILO tripartite structure, as well as with civil society / private sector through social dialogue, policy development forum for effective activity implementation; 
•	Developed strategies to address the linkages between HIV/AIDS and Child Labour in qualitative and quantitative terms within the Africa region; and
•	Innovative mobilisation and sustainable involvement of various ILO stakeholders across the African region in the fight against AIDS.

Brief description of duties and responsibilities 
•	Worked with civil society groups and CBOs to backstop UNIFEM project activities in the field; 
•	Managed relations between UNIFEM and its stakeholders and constituencies in the West Africa sub-region;  

Key achievements 
•	Key Member of the team that developed the advocacy strategy and content for reaching community-based groups for the UNIFEM Regional Programme on “Violence Against Women” launched in December 1999; 
•	Facilitated the efforts of UNIFEM to raise awareness on violence against women and young girls in colleges and tertiary institutions.
